{"type":"message","id":"6860d70f","parentId":"6d8d9faf","timestamp":"2026-03-22T14:54:19.878Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Chrome processes are running but none are listening on 9222. This is probably Chrome's metro/winrt mode which doesn't support remote debugging the same way. \n\nActually, looking at this - Chrome on Windows with `--remote-debugging-port` should work. But there might be an issue with how Chrome is running. Let me check if the issue is that the Chrome instances are using the newer Windows UI framework rather than the traditional executable.\n\nLet me try a different approach - check what the actual chrome executable path is and see if we can get the debug port working. Or maybe Chrome is running in \"service\" mode and not exposing the port.\n\nActually wait - Chrome on Windows 10/11 with the newer UI sometimes has issues with the traditional debugging approach. Let me check if there's a chrome instance running with debug mode or if we need to use a different approach.\n\nLet me try to connect to what should be the debugging endpoint and see what happens.","thinkingSignature":"8143f0caa4d60daaf27efd144119670ec72d60e11c9400acb4e9b158d37d52c6"},{"type":"text","text":"Chrome's running but not on 9222 — looks like it started without the debug flag. Did you add it to the shortcut? The easiest fix:\n\n**Step 1:** Close all Chrome windows completely\n\n**Step 2:** Run this in PowerShell or Command Prompt:\n```\nchrome.exe --remote-debugging-port=9222\n```\n\nOr if you prefer a permanent setup, right-click your Chrome shortcut → **Properties** → in the Target field, add the flag at the end:\n```\n\"C:\\Program Files\\Google\\Chrome\\Application\\chrome.exe\" --remote-debugging-port=9222\n```\n\nTry that and let me know when it's running."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":6889,"output":329,"cacheRead":12333,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19551,"cost":{