{"type":"message","id":"fe58bf4e","parentId":"ec30a09a","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:06:19.971Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Paperspace CLI isn't installable via pip or npm easily. Let me try a different approach - maybe I can find the templateId by trying common Paperspace template IDs, or I can try the Gradient API which might be easier.\n\nActually wait - let me think about this. Maybe the easier path is to use Paperspace Gradient to run Chrome in a Docker container. Gradient supports Docker containers with GPU support. But we don't need GPU for the browser box.\n\nOr - I could use a different cloud provider that's easier to provision. But Zach specifically said Paperspace.\n\nLet me look at the Paperspace API docs more carefully. The error said `templateId` is required. Let me try some common template IDs for Ubuntu 22.04 on Paperspace Core.\n\n\nActually, maybe I'm overthinking this. Let me just ask Zach to create the Core machine through the web console and hand me the SSH credentials - that绕过所有的 API 复杂性。","thinkingSignature":"1f88022e3b6d99b838c0ad4e0461bbe0db9bc480abc35757d41bbd7b90aec917"},{"type":"text","text":"API key works but the CLI isn't installable that way and the machine creation API needs a `templateId` I can't auto-discover. \n\nEasiest path forward: **you create the Core machine by hand in the Paperspace console** (takes 2 min), give me the public IP + SSH password/key, and I take it from there.\n\nSteps:\n1. Go to [console.paperspace.com](https://console.paperspace.com) → **Core** → **Create Machine**\n2. Pick: **Ubuntu 22.04**, **4 vCPU / 8GB RAM**, attach a public IP\n3. When it's running, paste me the IP + login credentials\n\nThen I'll SSH in, install Chrome + xvfb + noVNC, and we share the browser. \n\nAlternatively, if you want to avoid the console entirely, you could spin up a Gradient notebook (which you already know how to do) and I can install a VNC/Chrome stack in it — works fine, just uses a