{"type":"message","id":"94df22c7","parentId":"da64ef8c","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:07:07.030Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach's right - he only has Gradient, not Core. Gradient is Paperspace's notebook product. I shouldn't have suggested Core when I already knew his setup from TOOLS.md (which mentions \"Paperspace Gradient\" and \"A5000\"). \n\nSo I need to work with Gradient. Let me think about how to do a shared browser setup using Gradient notebooks.\n\nGradient notebooks:\n- Run in containers/VMs managed by Paperspace\n- Can have custom storage\n- Can they run Chrome? Usually Gradient notebooks run in a Docker container environment. It might be Ubuntu-based but may not support a full desktop environment.\n\nActually, let me think - Gradient has \"persistent storage\" and you can create custom runtimes. \n\nBut can you run Chrome + noVNC inside a Gradient notebook? That's the real question here. The notebook environment might be too sandboxed to run a full browser with a GUI, even with persistent storage and custom Dockerfiles. I could set up a VNC server inside the container, but Chrome might not work in a headless container environment without additional configuration.\n\nThe better approach would be to create a new Gradient notebook with a custom Dockerfile that includes xvfb (virtual framebuffer) for running Chrome headless, then use noVNC to provide web-based access. This way Chrome can run in the container and we can both view and control it through the browser. Let me look into how to actually set this up.\n\nFor the Gradient notebook itself, I can use the Paperspace API to create a notebook with a custom Docker container. The API endpoint would be POST to `https://api.paperspace.com/v1/notebooks` with the necessary parameters like machine type, Docker image, and volume size. The main constraint is figuring out whether Gradient notebooks support x86_64/amd64 architecture and whether we can actually run a full browser inside them.\n\nMy approach would be to create a Gradient notebook with a Dockerfile that includes Chrome and xvfb for headless rendering, then set up noVNC to provide web-based access to the graphical environment. This way both Zach and I can view and interact with the same browser instance through a shared URL. The container would run the noVNC server and Chrome together, with the VNC server connected to the virtual display.","thinkingSignature":"6dd15cdb073d7e033ebf37b8f68649039d9e51cab2c8017acaf9e9e5fd40cec4"},{"type":"text","text":"Right, my bad — I knew that. Let's do it with Gradient then.\n\nI can spin up a Gradient notebook with a custom Dockerfile that runs Chrome + noVNC inside it. Both of us get a web URL, same browser, seamless handoff.\n\nPlan:\n1. Create a new Gradient notebook (CPU is fine — browser doesn't need GPU)\n2. Custom Dockerfile: Ubuntu + Chrome + xvfb (virtual display) + noVNC\n3. I SSH into the running container via Gradient's workspace\n4. Start Chrome in the container, noVNC streams it to a URL you open\n\nThis is actually cleaner than Core — same infrastructure you already use, no new service to manage.\n\nWant me to draft the Dockerfile + setup script while you spin up the notebook, or do you want to walk through it together?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":633,"cacheRead":12333,"cacheWrite":13546,"totalTokens":26555,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774192001984}}
{"type":"message","id":"57c36409","parentId":"94df22c7","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:08:19.965Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sun 2026-03-22 11:08 EDT] go ahead"}],"timestamp":1774192099962}}
{"type":"message","id":"4179082c","parentId":"57c36409","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:08:45.572Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants me to go ahead and draft the Dockerfile and setup. Let me create the files needed for the Gradient notebook with Chrome + noVNC.\n\nThe approach:\n1. A Dockerfile that installs Chrome + xvfb + noVNC + OpenBox (lightweight window manager)\n2. A startup script that launches the browser in headless mode with CDP\n3. A notebook spec file for Gradient\n\nActually, for Gradient notebooks, I need to think about how to set this up. Gradient notebooks run in Docker containers. The way to access them is through the notebook interface or via SSH if they've enabled it.\n\nLet me think about the architecture:\n\n\n- Chrome with xvfb (virtual framebuffer) for headless rendering\n- noVNC to stream the virtual display to a browser-accessible URL\n- Both Zach and I access the same noVNC URL\n\nNow I need to create the setup files: a Dockerfile that installs all the necessary components, a startup script to initialize everything, and a Gradient notebook spec file to define how this runs on their infrastructure.\n\nFor the Dockerfile, I'll need to pull an Ubuntu base, install Chrome, xvfb, noVNC, and a minimal window manager like OpenBox. The tricky part is that Chrome needs to run with specific flags—`--no-sandbox` for containerized environments and `--remote-debugging-port=9222` to enable the DevTools protocol that noVNC can connect to.\n\nActually, I'm realizing noVNC talks to a separate VNC server rather than directly to Chrome's debugging port. So the flow would be: Chrome renders to the xvfb virtual display, a VNC server captures that display, and noVNC proxies the VNC connection to the browser. That's the standard headless setup.\n\nLet me sketch out the core files needed—Dockerfile, entrypoint script, and then the Gradient-specific configuration to get this deployed.\n\nFor Gradient, I could either use a Dockerfile build with a custom Docker runtime, or go simpler with a shell script notebook that installs everything at startup. The shell script approach probably has better compatibility across their system, though I should verify what GPU-enabled options they support on the A5000 machines.\n\nLet me draft the Dockerfile and setup script first, then figure out how to get them onto Zach's Gradient environment.","thinkingSignature":"78ed46576f9c2dc9a46c07ec12f849a617ca773a6130090f05d18989dc91f976"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me build the Dockerfile and setup script. I'll write them to your workspace so they're ready to drop into a Gradient notebook.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u5r1vf5f9reh_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1.4\nFROM ubuntu:22.04\n\nENV DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive\n\n# Install Chrome, xvfb, VNC, noVNC, OpenBox\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \\\n    wget \\\n    gnupg2 \\\n    ca-certificates \\\n    apt-transport-https \\\n    unzip \\\n    xauth \\\n    xvfb \\\n    libdbus-1-3 \\\n    libasound2 \\\n    libatk1.0-0 \\\n    libatk-bridge2.0-0 \\\n    libcups2 \\\n    libdrm2 \\\n    libxkbcommon0 \\\n    libxcomposite1 \\\n    libxdamage1 \\\n    libxfixes3 \\\n    libxrandr2 \\\n    libgbm1 \\\n    libpango-1.0-0 \\\n    libcairo2 \\\n    libatspi2.0-0 \\\n    libsecret-1-0 \\\n    openbox \\\n    x11vnc \\\n    websockify \\\n    novnc \\\n    && apt-get clean \\\n    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n# Install Chrome (latest stable)\nRUN wget -q -O /tmp/chrome.deb https://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/deb/pool/main/g/google-chrome-stable/google-chrome-stable_$(wget -q -O - https://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/deb/dists/stable/release.basesql | grep -oP 'Version: \\K[^ ]+' | head -1)_amd64.deb \\\n    && apt-get install -y /tmp/chrome.deb \\\n    && rm /tmp/chrome.deb\n\n# Copy startup script\nCOPY startup.sh /startup.sh\nRUN chmod +x /startup.sh\n\nEXPOSE 8080 5900 9222\n\nCMD [\"/startup.sh\"]\n","file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\nova-browser\\Dockerfile"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":948,"cacheRead":26149,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":27097,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774192099964}}
{"type":"message","id":"d1c28dfa","parentId":"4179082c","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:08:45.588Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_u5r1vf5f9reh_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 1169 bytes to C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\nova-browser\\Dockerfile"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774192125582}}
{"type":"message","id":"ed89a1be","parentId":"d1c28dfa","timestamp":"2026-03-22T15:08:58.695Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me write the startup script that launches everything.","thinkingSignature":"117bec10b8943251e035273828d3e189b829d468426b4b68406ccc00939b74d8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qw2f0hzuvman_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/bin/bash\nset -e\n\necho \"🚀 Nova Browser starting up...\"\n\n# Start Xvfb (virtual display :1, 1920x1080, 24bit color)\necho \"📺 Starting virtual display...\"\nXvfb :1 -screen 0 1920x1080x24 &\nXVFB_PID=$!\nexport DISPLAY=:1\n\nsleep 1\n\n# Start OpenBox (lightweight window manager)\necho \"🪟 Starting window manager...\"\nopenbox &\nsleep 1\n\n# Start Chrome with remote debugging + no-sandbox\necho \"🌐 Starting Chrome...\"\ngoogle-chrome \\\n    --no-sandbox \\\n    --disable-gpu \\\n    --disable-dev-shm-usage \\\n    --remote-debugging-port=9222 \\\n    --remote-debugging-address=0.0.0.0 \\\n    --kiosk \\\n    --app=https://www.google.com \\\n    &\n\nCHROME_PID=$!\nsleep 2\n\n# Start x11vnc (share the X display)\necho \"🔗 Starting VNC server...\"\nx11vnc -display :1 -nopw -listen localhost -xkb -ncache 10 -ncache_cr -forever -shared -rfbport 5900 &\n\nsleep 1\n\n# Start noVNC (WebSocket-to-VNC proxy on port 8080)\necho \"🖥️  Starting noVNC...\"\ncd /usr/share/novnc && ./utils/launch.sh --vnc localhost:5900 --listen 8080 &\n\nsleep 1\n\necho \"\"\necho \"✅ Nova Browser is live!\"\necho \"   noVNC (browser view):  http://localhost:8080/vnc.html\"\necho \"   Chrome DevTools:       http://localhost:9222\"\necho \"\"\n\n# Keep container alive\nwait\n","file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\nova-browser\\startup.sh"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14804,"output":447,"cacheRead":12333,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":27584,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total